everything post-90s for the entire DoD and private weapons sector got really bad for development. Budget and manpower were significantly reduced in early 2010s during sequestration

They tried to explain but I think in the long run we are hurting ourselves https://t.co/9fYh5cnF19

I guess I never understood that, people expecting immediate results... I think I was at Sheppard for temp duty around the exact time people started complaining so much

That was like in 2016

but then you start to realize that the F-22 has been in development since the 80s

But that the F-15 and F-16, which still BOTH get constant upgrades, started in the 60s

so why compared a less than 20 year old aircraft to aircraft that are nearly 60 years old

but like... it's only really been in developing the past 15+ years, and not even really operational until the past 5 years or so... which seems like a really long time but again, barely ever actually used compared to other aircraft

there is also the problem of needing to use stuff in real-world situations. I remember F-35 discourse and how much people hate it but it's actually a really cool jet (all three versions) especially with AI stuff, drone integration and lots of new tech
(or if you are not doing enough training then you have a bunch of incompetent people who cannot use equipment, aircraft and vehicles effectively)

from the outside looking in, it looks like we're just wasting time and money

but if you don't do this stuff then you just end up like Russia right now with actual wasted money because half your stuff just doesn't work

all peacetime stuff our military does is literally just daily training and preparation 

there is a reason we constantly fly, use almost every vehicle and all of equipment, constantly have exercises, constantly use everything and look at everything
I always say in some theoretical, actual world war or major war, they can't do much to us because we actually take care of our stuff, do routine training

it all just degrades, goes bad, fails

that stuff does not last forever, it goes bad, especially anything electronic or computer based, but even just super basic conventional munitions can go really bad if it is just sitting there, with bad storage conditions, all that stuff.

Literally what I have been saying for years every time people actually think Russia or China can do anything lol

Money almost does not matter, nor does supply if you are not actually taking care of stockpile, equipment, etc. and not doing routine maintenance and inspections https://t.co/R4Pik9Sz6D

all the weird fucked up stuff I was saying for attention

Mercy and I are working out a lot of stuff but I want you guys to know she's really a very sweet person, I love her very much, I apologize for trying to deflect blame away from myself, for the embarrassing stuff I've said, blaming others for my own problems

"We say we are for the Union. The world will not forget that we say this. We know how to save the Union. The world knows we do know how to save it. We, even we here, hold the power and bear the responsibility." 

4/end

"We of this Congress and this administration will be remembered in spite of ourselves. No personal significance or insignificance can spare one or another of us. The fiery trial through which we pass will light us down in honor or dishonor to the latest generation." 3/

"The occasion is piled high with difficulty, and we must rise with the occasion. As our case is new, so we must think anew, and act anew. We must disenthrall ourselves, and then we shall save our country.

Fellow citizens, we cannot escape history." 2/

Bea and I don‚Äôt agree now but as a writer she was a role model once upon a time - and Suzanne Moore, Deborah Orr‚Ä¶ Even Julie Burchill! And then, to me, they shape shifted. They became the very subjects of their earlier critiques.

Questionable (from my perspective) feminists have always existed. I stopped being confused about this as a teenager when I read Andrea Dworkins Right Wing Women and Bea Cambells book on Tory women whose title that I forget.
@RozKaveney The older I get the more I think about those meetings. I found them in City Limits and came on my own. I was just 20.

I‚Äôll never forget the coat hanger. And I‚Äôll always connect the coat hanger to the manipulation of fear around gender difference. Bad blood. But I‚Äôll always think about joy. And hope. And the promise of a better gendered life. Good blood.

It all started as a kid when I asked my step mum why that magazine had a coat hanger dripping with blood on its front cover - and why did it have such a weird name (Spare Rib). And all these decades later and I‚Äôm worrying again about the coat hanger.

These days I want to do all I can to ensure that trans researchers get to work on trans. My job is to move over. I don‚Äôt think that I became a professor because of doing work on trans so early, though it certainly helped.

These projects weren‚Äôt ‚Äòsupported‚Äô by trans researchers, they were made by them. And while I always strive to assist them to build their careers through  for instance named publications, grant writing support, I, of course. benefit the most. I get promoted. Invited. Named.

The institution were excited-cutting edge, newsworthy, perfect for EDI auditing. It was an absolute no from me. Never. The success of my trans‚Äô projects were all because of the trans researchers - the wonderful @NotRightRuth for example.

I‚Äôd built up community relationships. I costed in activist groups as consultants. I employed trans and queer women. But it started to feel different. On getting my professorship it was assumed by the panel that I would become Professor of Transgender Studies.

I began to work on citizenship and critiques of rights based politics. I found I loved writing and began to get published (a lot!) I won more bids. Was invited to events. Got promoted. I had a profile. I was a cis woman. I was working on trans.

I did talk about my positionality but briefly and in what I now think was a very weak way. It was 2004, the GRA had passed. I got funding to look at the GRA. On this project I began to think a lot about doing the work as a cis woman.

Still no one raised my being cis. Other people in gender studies and sociology began to focus on trans issues in PhDs. My amazing friend @zowiedavy who I began to have this - and so many more - conversation with. I finished my PhD and wrote my first book.

People with so much joy and With significant trauma and mental health issues. So many people wanted to talk. For hours. There were so many more people I couldn‚Äôt interview. Something was shifting. Nadia had won Big Brother. People wanted to talk. And be heard.

I stayed for hours. For dinner. Into the evenings. I was doing repeat interviews so back I went. For almost a year. I also spoke to women who were more familiar to me, lesbian trans women, musicians, performers. And bus drivers and women without jobs.

I‚Äôd never spoke to a straight trans women before. Women who lived and loved their wives of decades but were definite they weren‚Äôt lesbian. Women who desired and were desired by straight men. Women whose politics were so different to mine. I didn‚Äôt know any Tories or even Liberals

‚ÄòReal life test‚Äô, public outings and job losses, loosing family and children. Violence. Abuse. Stigma. Shame. This was miles away from Chain Reaction. And I went to meetings and conferences - GENDES. Voice workshops. Discos. Ball gowns. Fancy hair and even fancier make up

But it worked. It was *all* about self determination and bodily autonomy. And i began to think about legal and medical practices - institutional regulation. I knew about the politics of performance and gender subversion. I went on to learn so much more.

Risk assessments didn‚Äôt exist and I travelled around the UK on the train alone, went to peoples houses. Met in bars or cafes. I interviewed 50 people-trans men and women. I‚Äôd go from an interview with a Drag King in Highgate one day to a country conservative councillor the next.

My plan was around subversive genders - it was about the London stuff.  For funding I had to broaden it out and it came to include trans women. I didn‚Äôt think about being cis. No one asked me - until much later - about being cis. It‚Äôs unreal to think that now.

I had a baby. Moved from London. Taught in Adult Ed and FE. I‚Äôd done a year of a part time self funded PhD in London - young women and rave. Left it to earn as a mum. Always had doing a PhD sitting in my head. And I met the perfect person at the right time and amazingly got funds
Women around me began social transitioning. My ex‚Äôs traumas made sense. Communities began to be formed. FtM London, Del ‚Äòs photos, Jack‚Äôs and Jay‚Äôs books. Stephen and Press for Change.
Coming from Greenham, this ‚Äòscene‚Äô made sense. I knew it‚Äôs people. It was as it had been. As it should be. Remaking gender. Twisting - and being twisted by - sex. Forging a different future.

I joined Feminist Against Censorship, recently formed by @RozKaveney I was the youngest and I was shy-I think for the first time in my life. I didn‚Äôt say much but I loved it. I was in awe. This was the early 1990s. Battles were about porn, leather. BDSM and body mod. Butch/femme

Lesbians hadn‚Äôt, in our lives, had sex in public, role played, performed. Performance was central. Politics of performance and rebellion. Politics of filth. And it was creative and so very funny. Smart. So I went out a lot. Going out, dressing up, acting out, was our politics.

It was also brilliant fun. For me as a young woman new to London to start a degree. Living with my partner who was trans before we knew that was different from Stone. Before we knew how to really think about it. Still, we were young. The clubs were raucous, so sexy. Outrageous.

Politics of the body and sexuality were central as now in the terf wars. Attempts by some feminists to police that which they saw as undesirable, perverted, in others. Battles raged. In lesbian community centres, bars, clubs. It was vicious.

And of course there was @stephenwhittle and @susanstryker Mine was about social movements and gender diverse (sub)cultures. A big focus was the relationship between feminism and trans. This way preceded terfism and linked to its forerunner the sex wars.

It also looked at communities of care. There were three other UK sociologists doing related work/Richard Ekins and Dave King‚Äôs joint work and @SuryaMonro5432 who had started her PhD a year before. Surya‚Äôs work was more policy focused than mine. Ekins and King‚Äôs more typography.

There is no way that I would/could do the PhD that I did now. As a cis woman it wouldn‚Äôt and couldn‚Äôt be done. I started it in 2000 - 22 years ago and finished 3 years later. It was a sociology of gender diversity - identity formation and practice, politics and communities.
